            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this opioid conversion calculator works</h2>
              <p>This tool uses a two‑step approach:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Convert the current opioid regimen to an approximate
                  <strong>oral morphine equivalent (OME)</strong> in mg per 24
                  hours.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Convert that OME to an equianalgesic dose of the target opioid
                  and apply a user‑selected dose reduction for incomplete
                  cross‑tolerance.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Step 1 – Converting to oral morphine equivalents (OME)</h3>
              <p>
                For each opioid and route, the calculator stores a factor that
                relates the 24‑hour dose to oral morphine. In simplified form:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong
                    >OME (mg/24h) = Current 24‑hour dose × Conversion factor to
                    oral morphine</strong
                  >
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Examples of the factors used (approximate, adult, chronic use):
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Oral morphine: factor = 1 (10 mg oral morphine ≡ 10 mg OME)
                </li>
                <li>
                  SC/IV morphine: factor ≈ 2 (5 mg SC/IV ≡ 10 mg oral morphine)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Oral oxycodone: factor ≈ 1.5 (6.6–7.5 mg oxycodone ≡ 10 mg
                  oral morphine)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Oral hydromorphone: factor ≈ 5 (2 mg hydromorphone ≡ 10 mg
                  oral morphine)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Oral codeine: factor ≈ 0.1 (100 mg codeine ≡ 10 mg oral
                  morphine)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Fentanyl patch: 1 mcg/h ≈ 2.4 mg oral morphine per 24 h (e.g.
                  25 mcg/h ≈ 60 mg OME)
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Step 2 – Converting OME to the target opioid</h3>
              <p>
                Once the OME is estimated, the calculator divides by the target
                opioid’s factor to obtain an <em>equianalgesic</em> dose:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong
                    >Target 24‑hour dose (no reduction) = OME ÷ Target factor to
                    oral morphine</strong
                  >
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Because of <strong>incomplete cross‑tolerance</strong>, the
                starting dose of the new opioid is usually reduced:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong
                    >Suggested starting dose = Target 24‑hour dose × (1 −
                    Reduction % / 100)</strong
                  >
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Clinical cautions and limitations</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Equianalgesic tables are based on population averages;
                  individual response can differ markedly.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Renal or hepatic impairment, age, frailty, cachexia, and drug
                  interactions can all increase opioid sensitivity.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Breakthrough doses are typically 1/10–1/6 of the total 24‑hour
                  opioid dose, given every 2–4 hours as needed.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Transdermal fentanyl and buprenorphine have delayed onset and
                  offset; dose changes must be made cautiously.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Methadone is <strong>not</strong> included because its
                  conversion is highly non‑linear and specialist‑only.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>
                <strong>Scenario:</strong> A patient is taking oral morphine 30
